msgid "Idaṃ, bhikkhave, tatiyaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā sassatavādā sassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti. (3: 3) "
msgstr "This is the third ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the self and the cosmos are eternal. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs1.34, sc65
msgctxt "dn1:1.34.1"
msgid "Catutthe ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha sassatavādā sassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti? "
msgstr "And what is the fourth ground on which they rely? "

msgctxt "dn1:1.34.2"
msgid "Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā takkī hoti vīmaṃsī, so takkapariyāhataṃ vīmaṃsānucaritaṃ sayaṃ paṭibhānaṃ evamāha: "
msgstr "It’s when some ascetic or brahmin relies on logic and inquiry. They speak of what they have worked out by logic, following a line of inquiry, expressing their own perspective: "

msgctxt "dn1:1.34.3"
msgid "‘sassato attā ca loko ca vañjho kūṭaṭṭho esikaṭṭhāyiṭṭhito; "
msgstr "‘The self and the cosmos are eternal, barren, steady as a mountain peak, standing firm like a pillar. "

msgctxt "dn1:1.34.4"
msgid "te ca sattā sandhāvanti saṃsaranti cavanti upapajjanti, atthi tveva sassatisaman’ti. "
msgstr "They remain the same for all eternity, while these sentient beings wander and transmigrate and pass away and rearise.’ "

msgctxt "dn1:1.34.5"
msgid "Idaṃ, bhikkhave, catutthaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā sassatavādā sassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti. (4: 4) "
msgstr "This is the fourth ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the self and the cosmos are eternal. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs1.35, sc66
msgctxt "dn1:1.35.1"
msgid "Imehi kho te, bhikkhave, samaṇabrāhmaṇā sassatavādā sassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi. "
msgstr "These are the four grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins assert that the self and the cosmos are eternal. "

# NOTE: I have my doubts about this phrase: in every other occurrence, ito bahiddha means “outside of the Buddhist community”. Still, comm and the Chinese text at T21 agree on this sense.
msgctxt "dn1:1.35.2"
msgid "Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā sassatavādā sassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti, sabbe te imeheva catūhi vatthūhi, etesaṃ vā aññatarena; natthi ito bahiddhā. "
msgstr "Any ascetics and brahmins who assert that the self and the cosmos are eternal do so on one or other of these four grounds. Outside of this there is none. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs1.36, pts-vp-pli1.17, sc67
msgctxt "dn1:1.36.1"
msgid "Tayidaṃ, bhikkhave, tathāgato pajānāti: "
msgstr "The Realized One understands this: "

msgctxt "dn1:1.36.2"
msgid "‘ime diṭṭhiṭṭhānā evaṃgahitā evaṃparāmaṭṭhā evaṃgatikā bhavanti evaṃabhisamparāyā’ti, "
msgstr "‘If you hold on to and attach to these grounds for views it leads to such and such a destiny in the next life.’ "

#. VAR: pajānanaṃ → pajānaṃ (?)
msgctxt "dn1:1.36.3"
msgid "tañca tathāgato pajānāti, tato ca uttaritaraṃ pajānāti; tañca pajānanaṃ na parāmasati, aparāmasato cassa paccattaññeva nibbuti viditā. "
msgstr "He understands this, and what goes beyond this. Yet since he does not misapprehend that understanding, he has realized extinguishment within himself. "

msgctxt "dn1:1.36.4"
msgid "Vedanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ viditvā anupādāvimutto, bhikkhave, tathāgato. "
msgstr "Having truly understood the origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape from feelings, the Realized One is freed through not grasping. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs1.37, sc68
msgctxt "dn1:1.37.1"
msgid "Ime kho te, bhikkhave, dhammā gambhīrā duddasā duranubodhā santā paṇītā atakkāvacarā nipuṇā paṇḍitavedanīyā, ye tathāgato sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti, yehi tathāgatassa yathābhuccaṃ vaṇṇaṃ sammā vadamānā vadeyyuṃ. "
msgstr "These are the principles—deep, hard to see, hard to understand, peaceful, sublime, beyond the scope of reason, subtle, comprehensible to the astute—which the Realized One makes known after realizing them with his own insight. And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things. "

#. HTML: </p><p class="endsection">
msgctxt "dn1:1.37.2"
msgid "Paṭhamabhāṇavāro. "
msgstr " "

#. HTML: </p><h4>
msgctxt "dn1:1.37.3"
msgid "3.1.2. Ekaccasassatavāda "
msgstr "3.1.2. Partial Eternalism "

#. HTML: </h4><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.1, sc69
msgctxt "dn1:2.1.1"
msgid "Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi. "
msgstr "There are some ascetics and brahmins who are partial eternalists, who assert that the self and the cosmos are partially eternal and partially not eternal on four grounds. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.1.2"
msgid "Te ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi? "
msgstr "And what are the four grounds on which they rely? "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.2, sc70
msgctxt "dn1:2.2.1"
msgid "Hoti kho so, bhikkhave, samayo, yaṃ kadāci karahaci dīghassa addhuno accayena ayaṃ loko saṃvaṭṭati. "
msgstr "There comes a time when, after a very long period has passed, this cosmos contracts. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.2.2"
msgid "Saṃvaṭṭamāne loke yebhuyyena sattā ābhassarasaṃvattanikā honti. "
msgstr "As the cosmos contracts, sentient beings are mostly headed for the realm of streaming radiance. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.2.3"
msgid "Te tattha honti manomayā pītibhakkhā sayaṃpabhā antalikkhacarā subhaṭṭhāyino, ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ tiṭṭhanti. "
msgstr "There they are mind-made, feeding on rapture, self-luminous, moving through the sky, steadily glorious, and they remain like that for a very long time. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.3, sc71
msgctxt "dn1:2.3.1"
msgid "Hoti kho so, bhikkhave, samayo, yaṃ kadāci karahaci dīghassa addhuno accayena ayaṃ loko vivaṭṭati. "
msgstr "There comes a time when, after a very long period has passed, this cosmos expands. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.3.2"
msgid "Vivaṭṭamāne loke suññaṃ brahmavimānaṃ pātubhavati. "
msgstr "As it expands an empty mansion of Brahmā appears. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.3.3"
msgid "Atha kho aññataro satto āyukkhayā vā puññakkhayā vā ābhassarakāyā cavitvā suññaṃ brahmavimānaṃ upapajjati. "
msgstr "Then a certain sentient being—due to the running out of their life-span or merit—passes away from that host of radiant deities and is reborn in that empty mansion of Brahmā. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.3.4"
msgid "So tattha hoti manomayo pītibhakkho sayampabho antalikkhacaro subhaṭṭhāyī, ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ tiṭṭhati. "
msgstr "There they are mind-made, feeding on rapture, self-luminous, moving through the sky, steadily glorious, and they remain like that for a very long time. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.4, pts-vp-pli1.18, sc72
#. VAR: uppajjati → upapajjati (s1-3, c1)
msgctxt "dn1:2.4.1"
msgid "Tassa tattha ekakassa dīgharattaṃ nivusitattā anabhirati paritassanā uppajjati: "
msgstr "But after staying there all alone for a long time, they become dissatisfied and anxious: "

msgctxt "dn1:2.4.2"
msgid "‘aho vata aññepi sattā itthattaṃ āgaccheyyun’ti. "
msgstr "‘Oh, if only another being would come to this state of existence.’ "

msgctxt "dn1:2.4.3"
msgid "Atha aññepi sattā āyukkhayā vā puññakkhayā vā ābhassarakāyā cavitvā brahmavimānaṃ upapajjanti tassa sattassa sahabyataṃ. "
msgstr "Then other sentient beings—due to the running out of their life-span or merit—pass away from that host of radiant deities and are reborn in that empty mansion of Brahmā in company with that being. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.4.4"
msgid "Tepi tattha honti manomayā pītibhakkhā sayaṃpabhā antalikkhacarā subhaṭṭhāyino, ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ tiṭṭhanti. "
msgstr "There they too are mind-made, feeding on rapture, self-luminous, moving through the sky, steadily glorious, and they remain like that for a very long time. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.5, sc73
msgctxt "dn1:2.5.1"
msgid "Tatra, bhikkhave, yo so satto paṭhamaṃ upapanno tassa evaṃ hoti: "
msgstr "Now, the being who was reborn there first thinks: "

#. VAR: sajitā → sajjitā (s1-3, km) | sañjitā (pts1)
msgctxt "dn1:2.5.2"
msgid "‘ahamasmi brahmā mahābrahmā abhibhū anabhibhūto aññadatthudaso vasavattī issaro kattā nimmātā seṭṭho sajitā vasī pitā bhūtabhabyānaṃ. "
msgstr "‘I am Brahmā, the Great Brahmā, the Undefeated, the Champion, the Universal Seer, the Wielder of Power, the Lord God, the Maker, the Author, the Best, the Begetter, the Controller, the Father of those who have been born and those yet to be born. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.5.3"
msgid "Mayā ime sattā nimmitā. "
msgstr "These beings were created by me! "

msgctxt "dn1:2.5.4"
msgid "Taṃ kissa hetu? "
msgstr "Why is that? "

msgctxt "dn1:2.5.5"
msgid "Mamañhi pubbe etadahosi: "
msgstr "Because first I thought: "

#. HTML: </p><p>
msgctxt "dn1:2.5.6"
msgid "“aho vata aññepi sattā itthattaṃ āgaccheyyun”ti. "
msgstr "“Oh, if only another being would come to this state of existence.” "

# NOTE: Correlation and causation!
#. VAR: mama ca → mamañca (bj, s1-3, pts1)
msgctxt "dn1:2.5.7"
msgid "Iti mama ca manopaṇidhi, ime ca sattā itthattaṃ āgatā’ti. "
msgstr "Such was my heart’s wish, and then these creatures came to this state of existence.’ "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc74
#. VAR: upapannā → uppannā (si)
msgctxt "dn1:2.5.8"
msgid "Yepi te sattā pacchā upapannā, tesampi evaṃ hoti: "
msgstr "And the beings who were reborn there later also think: "

msgctxt "dn1:2.5.9"
msgid "‘ayaṃ kho bhavaṃ brahmā mahābrahmā abhibhū anabhibhūto aññadatthudaso vasavattī issaro kattā nimmātā seṭṭho sajitā vasī pitā bhūtabhabyānaṃ. "
msgstr "‘This must be Brahmā, the Great Brahmā, the Undefeated, the Champion, the Universal Seer, the Wielder of Power, the Lord God, the Maker, the Author, the Best, the Begetter, the Controller, the Father of those who have been born and those yet to be born. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.5.10"
msgid "Iminā mayaṃ bhotā brahmunā nimmitā. "
msgstr "And we have been created by him. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.5.11"
msgid "Taṃ kissa hetu? "
msgstr "Why is that? "

msgctxt "dn1:2.5.12"
msgid "Imañhi mayaṃ addasāma idha paṭhamaṃ upapannaṃ, mayaṃ panamha pacchā upapannā’ti. "
msgstr "Because we see that he was reborn here first, and we arrived later.’ "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.6, sc75
msgctxt "dn1:2.6.1"
msgid "Tatra, bhikkhave, yo so satto paṭhamaṃ upapanno, so dīghāyukataro ca hoti vaṇṇavantataro ca mahesakkhataro ca. "
msgstr "And the being who was reborn first is more long-lived, beautiful, and illustrious than those who arrived later. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.6.2"
msgid "Ye pana te sattā pacchā upapannā, te appāyukatarā ca honti dubbaṇṇatarā ca appesakkhatarā ca. "
msgstr " "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc76
msgctxt "dn1:2.6.3"
msgid "Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, bhikkhave, vijjati, yaṃ aññataro satto tamhā kāyā cavitvā itthattaṃ āgacchati. "
msgstr "It’s possible that one of those beings passes away from that host and is reborn in this state of existence. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.6.4"
msgid "Itthattaṃ āgato samāno agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati. "
msgstr "Having done so, they go forth from the lay life to homelessness. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.6.5"
msgid "Agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito samāno ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte taṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati, tato paraṃ nānussarati. "
msgstr "By dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus, they experience an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they recollect that past life, but no further. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-vp-pli1.19, sc77
msgctxt "dn1:2.6.6"
msgid "So evamāha: "
msgstr "They say: "

msgctxt "dn1:2.6.7"
msgid "‘yo kho so bhavaṃ brahmā mahābrahmā abhibhū anabhibhūto aññadatthudaso vasavattī issaro kattā nimmātā seṭṭho sajitā vasī pitā bhūtabhabyānaṃ, yena mayaṃ bhotā brahmunā nimmitā, so nicco dhuvo sassato avipariṇāmadhammo sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassati. "
msgstr "‘He who is Brahmā—the Great Brahmā, the Undefeated, the Champion, the Universal Seer, the Wielder of Power, the Lord God, the Maker, the Author, the Best, the Begetter, the Controller, the Father of those who have been born and those yet to be born—is permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, remaining the same for all eternity. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.6.8"
msgid "Ye pana mayaṃ ahumhā tena bhotā brahmunā nimmitā, te mayaṃ aniccā addhuvā appāyukā cavanadhammā itthattaṃ āgatā’ti. "
msgstr "We who were created by that Brahmā are impermanent, not lasting, short-lived, perishable, and have come to this state of existence. "

#. VAR: Idaṃ → idaṃ kho (c1)
msgctxt "dn1:2.6.9"
msgid "Idaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti. (1: 5) "
msgstr "This is the first ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the self and the cosmos are partially eternal. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.7, sc78
msgctxt "dn1:2.7.1"
msgid "Dutiye ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti? "
msgstr "And what is the second ground on which they rely? "

#. VAR: sammussati → mussati (bj, pts1) | pamussati (s1-3)
msgctxt "dn1:2.7.2"
msgid "Santi, bhikkhave, khiḍḍāpadosikā nāma devā, te ativelaṃ hassakhiḍḍāratidhammasamāpannā viharanti. Tesaṃ ativelaṃ hassakhiḍḍāratidhammasamāpannānaṃ viharataṃ sati sammussati. Satiyā sammosā te devā tamhā kāyā cavanti. "
msgstr "There are gods named ‘depraved by play.’ They spend too much time laughing, playing, and making merry. And in doing so, they lose their mindfulness, and they pass away from that host of gods. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.8, sc79
msgctxt "dn1:2.8.1"
msgid "Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, bhikkhave, vijjati yaṃ aññataro satto tamhā kāyā cavitvā itthattaṃ āgacchati. "
msgstr "It’s possible that one of those beings passes away from that host and is reborn in this state of existence. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.8.2"
msgid "Itthattaṃ āgato samāno agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati. "
msgstr "Having done so, they go forth from the lay life to homelessness. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.8.3"
msgid "Agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito samāno ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte taṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati, tato paraṃ nānussarati. "
msgstr "By dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus, they experience an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they recollect that past life, but no further. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.9, pts-vp-pli1.20, sc80
msgctxt "dn1:2.9.1"
msgid "So evamāha: "
msgstr "They say: "

msgctxt "dn1:2.9.2"
msgid "‘ye kho te bhonto devā na khiḍḍāpadosikā, te na ativelaṃ hassakhiḍḍāratidhammasamāpannā viharanti. Tesaṃ na ativelaṃ hassakhiḍḍāratidhammasamāpannānaṃ viharataṃ sati na sammussati. Satiyā asammosā te devā tamhā kāyā na cavanti; "
msgstr "‘The gods not depraved by play don’t spend too much time laughing, playing, and making merry. So they don’t lose their mindfulness, and don’t pass away from that host of gods. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.9.3"
msgid "niccā dhuvā sassatā avipariṇāmadhammā sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassanti. "
msgstr "They are permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, remaining the same for all eternity. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.9.4"
msgid "Ye pana mayaṃ ahumhā khiḍḍāpadosikā, te mayaṃ ativelaṃ hassakhiḍḍāratidhammasamāpannā viharimhā. Tesaṃ no ativelaṃ hassakhiḍḍāratidhammasamāpannānaṃ viharataṃ sati sammussati. Satiyā sammosā evaṃ mayaṃ tamhā kāyā cutā "
msgstr "But we who were depraved by play spent too much time laughing, playing, and making merry. In doing so, we lost our mindfulness, and passed away from that host of gods. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.9.5"
msgid "aniccā addhuvā appāyukā cavanadhammā itthattaṃ āgatā’ti. "
msgstr "We are impermanent, not lasting, short-lived, perishable, and have come to this state of existence.’ "

msgctxt "dn1:2.9.6"
msgid "Idaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti. (2: 6) "
msgstr "This is the second ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the self and the cosmos are partially eternal. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.10, sc81
msgctxt "dn1:2.10.1"
msgid "Tatiye ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti? "
msgstr "And what is the third ground on which they rely? "

# NOTE: The parallel with khiddapadosika rather confuses the issue, suggesting a rendering “depraved in mind” here. However elsewhere in the suttas, manopadosa consistently means “malicious intent”, MN 56, MN 93, also see mano padūseyya at MN 21 and MN 28. Thus the contrast here would seem to be greed vs hate. Also note DN 26, “tesaṃ sattānaṃ aññamaññamhi tibbo āghāto paccupaṭṭhito bhavissati tibbo byāpādo tibbo manopadoso tibbaṃ vadhakacittaṃ.”
msgctxt "dn1:2.10.2"
msgid "Santi, bhikkhave, manopadosikā nāma devā, te ativelaṃ aññamaññaṃ upanijjhāyanti. Te ativelaṃ aññamaññaṃ upanijjhāyantā aññamaññamhi cittāni padūsenti. Te aññamaññaṃ paduṭṭhacittā kilantakāyā kilantacittā. Te devā tamhā kāyā cavanti. "
msgstr "There are gods named ‘malevolent’. They spend too much time gazing at each other, so they grow angry with each other, and their bodies and minds get tired. They pass away from that host of gods. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.11, sc82
msgctxt "dn1:2.11.1"
msgid "Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, bhikkhave, vijjati yaṃ aññataro satto tamhā kāyā cavitvā itthattaṃ āgacchati. "
msgstr "It’s possible that one of those beings passes away from that host and is reborn in this state of existence. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.11.2"
msgid "Itthattaṃ āgato samāno agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati. "
msgstr "Having done so, they go forth from the lay life to homelessness. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.11.3"
msgid "Agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito samāno ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte taṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati, tato paraṃ nānussarati. "
msgstr "By dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus, they experience an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they recollect that past life, but no further. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.12, pts-vp-pli1.21, sc83
msgctxt "dn1:2.12.1"
msgid "So evamāha: "
msgstr "They say: "

msgctxt "dn1:2.12.2"
msgid "‘ye kho te bhonto devā na manopadosikā, te nātivelaṃ aññamaññaṃ upanijjhāyanti. Te nātivelaṃ aññamaññaṃ upanijjhāyantā aññamaññamhi cittāni nappadūsenti. Te aññamaññaṃ appaduṭṭhacittā akilantakāyā akilantacittā. Te devā tamhā kāyā na cavanti, "
msgstr "‘The gods who are not malevolent don’t spend too much time gazing at each other, so they don’t grow angry with each other, their bodies and minds don’t get tired, and they don’t pass away from that host of gods. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.12.3"
msgid "niccā dhuvā sassatā avipariṇāmadhammā sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassanti. "
msgstr "They are permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, remaining the same for all eternity. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.12.4"
msgid "Ye pana mayaṃ ahumhā manopadosikā, te mayaṃ ativelaṃ aññamaññaṃ upanijjhāyimhā. Te mayaṃ ativelaṃ aññamaññaṃ upanijjhāyantā aññamaññamhi cittāni padūsimhā, te mayaṃ aññamaññaṃ paduṭṭhacittā kilantakāyā kilantacittā. Evaṃ mayaṃ tamhā kāyā cutā "
msgstr "But we who were malevolent spent too much time gazing at each other, we grew angry with each other, our bodies and minds got tired, and we passed away from that host of gods. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.12.5"
msgid "aniccā addhuvā appāyukā cavanadhammā itthattaṃ āgatā’ti. "
msgstr "We are impermanent, not lasting, short-lived, perishable, and have come to this state of existence.’ "

msgctxt "dn1:2.12.6"
msgid "Idaṃ, bhikkhave, tatiyaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti. (3: 7) "
msgstr "This is the third ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the self and the cosmos are partially eternal. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.13, sc84
msgctxt "dn1:2.13.1"
msgid "Catutthe ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti? "
msgstr "And what is the fourth ground on which they rely? "

msgctxt "dn1:2.13.2"
msgid "Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā takkī hoti vīmaṃsī. So takkapariyāhataṃ vīmaṃsānucaritaṃ sayampaṭibhānaṃ evamāha: "
msgstr "It’s when some ascetic or brahmin relies on logic and inquiry. They speak of what they have worked out by logic, following a line of inquiry, expressing their own perspective: "

msgctxt "dn1:2.13.3"
msgid "‘yaṃ kho idaṃ vuccati cakkhuṃ itipi sotaṃ itipi ghānaṃ itipi jivhā itipi kāyo itipi, ayaṃ attā anicco addhuvo asassato vipariṇāmadhammo. "
msgstr "‘That which is called “the eye” or “the ear” or “the nose” or “the tongue” or “the body”: that self is impermanent, not lasting, transient, perishable. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.13.4"
msgid "Yañca kho idaṃ vuccati cittanti vā manoti vā viññāṇanti vā ayaṃ attā nicco dhuvo sassato avipariṇāmadhammo sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassatī’ti. "
msgstr "That which is called “mind” or “sentience” or “consciousness”: that self is permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, remaining the same for all eternity.’ "

msgctxt "dn1:2.13.5"
msgid "Idaṃ, bhikkhave, catutthaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti. (4: 8) "
msgstr "This is the fourth ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the self and the cosmos are partially eternal. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.14, sc85
msgctxt "dn1:2.14.1"
msgid "Imehi kho te, bhikkhave, samaṇabrāhmaṇā ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi. "
msgstr "These are the four grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins assert that the self and the cosmos are partially eternal and partially not eternal. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.14.2"
msgid "Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti, sabbe te imeheva catūhi vatthūhi, etesaṃ vā aññatarena; natthi ito bahiddhā. "
msgstr "Any ascetics and brahmins who assert that the self and the cosmos are partially eternal and partially not eternal do so on one or other of these four grounds. Outside of this there is none. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.15, pts-vp-pli1.22, sc86
msgctxt "dn1:2.15.1"
msgid "Tayidaṃ, bhikkhave, tathāgato pajānāti: "
msgstr "The Realized One understands this: "

msgctxt "dn1:2.15.2"
msgid "‘ime diṭṭhiṭṭhānā evaṅgahitā evaṃparāmaṭṭhā evaṅgatikā bhavanti evaṃabhisamparāyā’ti. "
msgstr "‘If you hold on to and attach to these grounds for views it leads to such and such a destiny in the next life.’ "

msgctxt "dn1:2.15.3"
msgid "Tañca tathāgato pajānāti, tato ca uttaritaraṃ pajānāti, tañca pajānanaṃ na parāmasati, aparāmasato cassa paccattaññeva nibbuti viditā. "
msgstr "He understands this, and what goes beyond this. Yet since he does not misapprehend that understanding, he has realized extinguishment within himself. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.15.4"
msgid "Vedanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ viditvā anupādāvimutto, bhikkhave, tathāgato. "
msgstr "Having truly understood the origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape from feelings, the Realized One is freed through not grasping. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc87
msgctxt "dn1:2.15.5"
msgid "Ime kho te, bhikkhave, dhammā gambhīrā duddasā duranubodhā santā paṇītā atakkāvacarā nipuṇā paṇḍitavedanīyā, ye tathāgato sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti, yehi tathāgatassa yathābhuccaṃ vaṇṇaṃ sammā vadamānā vadeyyuṃ. "
msgstr "These are the principles—deep, hard to see, hard to understand, peaceful, sublime, beyond the scope of reason, subtle, comprehensible to the astute—which the Realized One makes known after realizing them with his own insight. And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things. "

#. HTML: </p><h4>
msgctxt "dn1:2.15.6"
msgid "3.1.3. Antānantavāda "
msgstr "3.1.3. The Cosmos is Finite or Infinite "

#. HTML: </h4><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.16, sc88
msgctxt "dn1:2.16.1"
msgid "Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi. "
msgstr "There are some ascetics and brahmins who theorize about size, and assert that the cosmos is finite or infinite on four grounds. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.16.2"
msgid "Te ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi? "
msgstr "And what are the four grounds on which they rely? "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.17, sc89
msgctxt "dn1:2.17.1"
msgid "Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte antasaññī lokasmiṃ viharati. "
msgstr "It’s when some ascetic or brahmin—by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus—experiences an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they meditate perceiving the cosmos as finite. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc90
msgctxt "dn1:2.17.2"
msgid "So evamāha: "
msgstr "They say: "

msgctxt "dn1:2.17.3"
msgid "‘antavā ayaṃ loko parivaṭumo. "
msgstr "‘The cosmos is finite and bounded. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.17.4"
msgid "Taṃ kissa hetu? "
msgstr "Why is that? "

msgctxt "dn1:2.17.5"
msgid "Ahañhi ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusāmi, yathāsamāhite citte antasaññī lokasmiṃ viharāmi. "
msgstr "Because by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus I experience an immersion of the heart of such a kind that I meditate perceiving the cosmos as finite. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.17.6"
msgid "Imināmahaṃ etaṃ jānāmi: "
msgstr "Because of this I know: "

#. HTML: </p><p>
msgctxt "dn1:2.17.7"
msgid "“yathā antavā ayaṃ loko parivaṭumo”’ti. "
msgstr "“The cosmos is finite and bounded.”’ "

msgctxt "dn1:2.17.8"
msgid "Idaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti. (1: 9) "
msgstr "This is the first ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the cosmos is finite or infinite. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.18, pts-vp-pli1.23, sc91
msgctxt "dn1:2.18.1"
msgid "Dutiye ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti? "
msgstr "And what is the second ground on which they rely? "

msgctxt "dn1:2.18.2"
msgid "Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte anantasaññī lokasmiṃ viharati. "
msgstr "It’s when some ascetic or brahmin—by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus—experiences an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they meditate perceiving the cosmos as infinite. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc92
msgctxt "dn1:2.18.3"
msgid "So evamāha: "
msgstr "They say: "

msgctxt "dn1:2.18.4"
msgid "‘ananto ayaṃ loko apariyanto. "
msgstr "‘The cosmos is infinite and unbounded. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.18.5"
msgid "Ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā evamāhaṃsu: "
msgstr "The ascetics and brahmins who say that "

msgctxt "dn1:2.18.6"
msgid "“antavā ayaṃ loko parivaṭumo”ti, tesaṃ musā. "
msgstr "the cosmos is finite are wrong. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.18.7"
msgid "Ananto ayaṃ loko apariyanto. "
msgstr "The cosmos is infinite and unbounded. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.18.8"
msgid "Taṃ kissa hetu? "
msgstr "Why is that? "

msgctxt "dn1:2.18.9"
msgid "Ahañhi ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusāmi, yathāsamāhite citte anantasaññī lokasmiṃ viharāmi. "
msgstr "Because by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus I experience an immersion of the heart of such a kind that I meditate perceiving the cosmos as infinite. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.18.10"
msgid "Imināmahaṃ etaṃ jānāmi: "
msgstr "Because of this I know: "

#. HTML: </p><p>
msgctxt "dn1:2.18.11"
msgid "“yathā ananto ayaṃ loko apariyanto”’ti. "
msgstr "“The cosmos is infinite and unbounded.”’ "

msgctxt "dn1:2.18.12"
msgid "Idaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti. (2: 10) "
msgstr "This is the second ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the cosmos is finite or infinite. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.19, sc93
msgctxt "dn1:2.19.1"
msgid "Tatiye ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti? "
msgstr "And what is the third ground on which they rely? "

msgctxt "dn1:2.19.2"
msgid "Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte uddhamadho antasaññī lokasmiṃ viharati, tiriyaṃ anantasaññī. "
msgstr "It’s when some ascetic or brahmin—by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus—experiences an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they meditate perceiving the cosmos as finite vertically but infinite horizontally. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc94
msgctxt "dn1:2.19.3"
msgid "So evamāha: "
msgstr "They say: "

msgctxt "dn1:2.19.4"
msgid "‘antavā ca ayaṃ loko ananto ca. "
msgstr "‘The cosmos is both finite and infinite. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.19.5"
msgid "Ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā evamāhaṃsu: "
msgstr "The ascetics and brahmins who say that "

msgctxt "dn1:2.19.6"
msgid "“antavā ayaṃ loko parivaṭumo”ti, tesaṃ musā. "
msgstr "the cosmos is finite are wrong, "

msgctxt "dn1:2.19.7"
msgid "Yepi te samaṇabrāhmaṇā evamāhaṃsu: "
msgstr "and so are those who say that "

msgctxt "dn1:2.19.8"
msgid "“ananto ayaṃ loko apariyanto”ti, tesampi musā. "
msgstr "the cosmos is infinite. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.19.9"
msgid "Antavā ca ayaṃ loko ananto ca. "
msgstr "The cosmos is both finite and infinite. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.19.10"
msgid "Taṃ kissa hetu? "
msgstr "Why is that? "

msgctxt "dn1:2.19.11"
msgid "Ahañhi ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusāmi, yathāsamāhite citte uddhamadho antasaññī lokasmiṃ viharāmi, tiriyaṃ anantasaññī. "
msgstr "Because by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus I experience an immersion of the heart of such a kind that I meditate perceiving the cosmos as finite vertically but infinite horizontally. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.19.12"
msgid "Imināmahaṃ etaṃ jānāmi: "
msgstr "Because of this I know: "

#. HTML: </p><p>
msgctxt "dn1:2.19.13"
msgid "“yathā antavā ca ayaṃ loko ananto cā”’ti. "
msgstr "“The cosmos is both finite and infinite.”’ "

msgctxt "dn1:2.19.14"
msgid "Idaṃ, bhikkhave, tatiyaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti. (3: 11) "
msgstr "This is the third ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the cosmos is finite or infinite. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.20, pts-vp-pli1.24, sc95
msgctxt "dn1:2.20.1"
msgid "Catutthe ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti? "
msgstr "And what is the fourth ground on which they rely? "

msgctxt "dn1:2.20.2"
msgid "Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā takkī hoti vīmaṃsī. So takkapariyāhataṃ vīmaṃsānucaritaṃ sayampaṭibhānaṃ evamāha: "
msgstr "It’s when some ascetic or brahmin relies on logic and inquiry. They speak of what they have worked out by logic, following a line of inquiry, expressing their own perspective: "

msgctxt "dn1:2.20.3"
msgid "‘nevāyaṃ loko antavā, na panānanto. "
msgstr "‘The cosmos is neither finite nor infinite. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.20.4"
msgid "Ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā evamāhaṃsu: "
msgstr "The ascetics and brahmins who say that "

msgctxt "dn1:2.20.5"
msgid "“antavā ayaṃ loko parivaṭumo”ti, tesaṃ musā. "
msgstr "the cosmos is finite are wrong, "

msgctxt "dn1:2.20.6"
msgid "Yepi te samaṇabrāhmaṇā evamāhaṃsu: "
msgstr "as are those who say that "

msgctxt "dn1:2.20.7"
msgid "“ananto ayaṃ loko apariyanto”ti, tesampi musā. "
msgstr "the cosmos is infinite, "

msgctxt "dn1:2.20.8"
msgid "Yepi te samaṇabrāhmaṇā evamāhaṃsu: "
msgstr "and also those who say that "

msgctxt "dn1:2.20.9"
msgid "“antavā ca ayaṃ loko ananto cā”ti, tesampi musā. "
msgstr "the cosmos is both finite and infinite. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.20.10"
msgid "Nevāyaṃ loko antavā, na panānanto’ti. "
msgstr "The cosmos is neither finite nor infinite.’ "

msgctxt "dn1:2.20.11"
msgid "Idaṃ, bhikkhave, catutthaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti. (4: 12) "
msgstr "This is the fourth ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the cosmos is finite or infinite. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.21, sc96
msgctxt "dn1:2.21.1"
msgid "Imehi kho te, bhikkhave, samaṇabrāhmaṇā antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi. "
msgstr "These are the four grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins assert that the cosmos is finite or infinite. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.21.2"
msgid "Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti, sabbe te imeheva catūhi vatthūhi, etesaṃ vā aññatarena; natthi ito bahiddhā. "
msgstr "Any ascetics and brahmins who assert that the cosmos is finite or infinite do so on one or other of these four grounds. Outside of this there is none. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.22, sc97
msgctxt "dn1:2.22.1"
msgid "Tayidaṃ, bhikkhave, tathāgato pajānāti: "
msgstr "The Realized One understands this: "

msgctxt "dn1:2.22.2"
msgid "‘ime diṭṭhiṭṭhānā evaṅgahitā evaṃparāmaṭṭhā evaṅgatikā bhavanti evaṃabhisamparāyā’ti. "
msgstr "‘If you hold on to and attach to these grounds for views it leads to such and such a destiny in the next life.’ "

msgctxt "dn1:2.22.3"
msgid "Tañca tathāgato pajānāti, tato ca uttaritaraṃ pajānāti, tañca pajānanaṃ na parāmasati, aparāmasato cassa paccattaññeva nibbuti viditā. "
msgstr "He understands this, and what goes beyond this. Yet since he does not misapprehend that understanding, he has realized extinguishment within himself. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.22.4"
msgid "Vedanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ viditvā anupādāvimutto, bhikkhave, tathāgato. "
msgstr "Having truly understood the origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape from feelings, the Realized One is freed through not grasping. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc98
msgctxt "dn1:2.22.5"
msgid "Ime kho te, bhikkhave, dhammā gambhīrā duddasā duranubodhā santā paṇītā atakkāvacarā nipuṇā paṇḍitavedanīyā, ye tathāgato sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti, yehi tathāgatassa yathābhuccaṃ vaṇṇaṃ sammā vadamānā vadeyyuṃ. "
msgstr "These are the principles—deep, hard to see, hard to understand, peaceful, sublime, beyond the scope of reason, subtle, comprehensible to the astute—which the Realized One makes known after realizing them with his own insight. And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things. "

#. HTML: </p><h4>
msgctxt "dn1:2.22.6"
msgid "3.1.4. Amarāvikkhepavāda "
msgstr "3.1.4. Equivocators "

#. HTML: </h4><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.23, sc99
msgctxt "dn1:2.23.1"
msgid "Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā amarāvikkhepikā, tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ catūhi vatthūhi. "
msgstr "There are some ascetics and brahmins who are equivocators. Whenever they’re asked a question, they resort to evasiveness and equivocation on four grounds. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.23.2"
msgid "Te ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha amarāvikkhepikā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ catūhi vatthūhi? "
msgstr "And what are the four grounds on which they rely? "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.24, pts-vp-pli1.25, sc100
msgctxt "dn1:2.24.1"
msgid "Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ‘idaṃ kusalan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti, ‘idaṃ akusalan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti. "
msgstr "It’s when some ascetic or brahmin doesn’t truly understand what is skillful and what is unskillful. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.24.2"
msgid "Tassa evaṃ hoti: "
msgstr "They think: "

msgctxt "dn1:2.24.3"
msgid "‘ahaṃ kho “idaṃ kusalan”ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāmi, “idaṃ akusalan”ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāmi. "
msgstr "‘I don’t truly understand what is skillful and what is unskillful. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.24.4"
msgid "Ahañce kho pana “idaṃ kusalan”ti yathābhūtaṃ appajānanto, “idaṃ akusalan”ti yathābhūtaṃ appajānanto, “idaṃ kusalan”ti vā byākareyyaṃ, “idaṃ akusalan”ti vā byākareyyaṃ, taṃ mamassa musā. "
msgstr "If I were to declare that something was skillful or unskillful I might be wrong. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.24.5"
msgid "Yaṃ mamassa musā, so mamassa vighāto. "
msgstr "That would be stressful for me, "

msgctxt "dn1:2.24.6"
msgid "Yo mamassa vighāto so mamassa antarāyo’ti. "
msgstr "and that stress would be an obstacle.’ "

msgctxt "dn1:2.24.7"
msgid "Iti so musāvādabhayā musāvādaparijegucchā nevidaṃ kusalanti byākaroti, na panidaṃ akusalanti byākaroti, tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭho samāno vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjati amarāvikkhepaṃ: "
msgstr "So from fear and disgust with false speech they avoid stating whether something is skillful or unskillful. Whenever they’re asked a question, they resort to evasiveness and equivocation: "

msgctxt "dn1:2.24.8"
msgid "‘evantipi me no; tathātipi me no; aññathātipi me no; notipi me no; no notipi me no’ti. "
msgstr "‘I don’t say it’s like this. I don’t say it’s like that. I don’t say it’s otherwise. I don’t say it’s not so. And I don’t deny it’s not so.’ "

msgctxt "dn1:2.24.9"
msgid "Idaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā amarāvikkhepikā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ. (1: 13) "
msgstr "This is the first ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely when resorting to evasiveness and equivocation. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.25, pts-vp-pli1.26, sc101
msgctxt "dn1:2.25.1"
msgid "Dutiye ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha amarāvikkhepikā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ? "
msgstr "And what is the second ground on which they rely? "

msgctxt "dn1:2.25.2"
msgid "Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ‘idaṃ kusalan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti, ‘idaṃ akusalan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti. "
msgstr "It’s when some ascetic or brahmin doesn’t truly understand what is skillful and what is unskillful. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.25.3"
msgid "Tassa evaṃ hoti: "
msgstr "They think: "

msgctxt "dn1:2.25.4"
msgid "‘ahaṃ kho “idaṃ kusalan”ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāmi, “idaṃ akusalan”ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāmi. "
msgstr "‘I don’t truly understand what is skillful and what is unskillful. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.25.5"
msgid "Ahañce kho pana “idaṃ kusalan”ti yathābhūtaṃ appajānanto, “idaṃ akusalan”ti yathābhūtaṃ appajānanto, “idaṃ kusalan”ti vā byākareyyaṃ, “idaṃ akusalan”ti vā byākareyyaṃ, tattha me assa chando vā rāgo vā doso vā paṭigho vā. "
msgstr "If I were to declare that something was skillful or unskillful I might feel desire or greed or hate or repulsion. "

#. VAR: Yattha → yo (?)
msgctxt "dn1:2.25.6"
msgid "Yattha me assa chando vā rāgo vā doso vā paṭigho vā, taṃ mamassa upādānaṃ. "
msgstr "That would be grasping on my part. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.25.7"
msgid "Yaṃ mamassa upādānaṃ, so mamassa vighāto. "
msgstr "That would be stressful for me, "

msgctxt "dn1:2.25.8"
msgid "Yo mamassa vighāto, so mamassa antarāyo’ti. "
msgstr "and that stress would be an obstacle.’ "

msgctxt "dn1:2.25.9"
msgid "Iti so upādānabhayā upādānaparijegucchā nevidaṃ kusalanti byākaroti, na panidaṃ akusalanti byākaroti, tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭho samāno vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjati amarāvikkhepaṃ: "
msgstr "So from fear and disgust with grasping they avoid stating whether something is skillful or unskillful. Whenever they’re asked a question, they resort to evasiveness and equivocation: "

msgctxt "dn1:2.25.10"
msgid "‘evantipi me no; tathātipi me no; aññathātipi me no; notipi me no; no notipi me no’ti. "
msgstr "‘I don’t say it’s like this. I don’t say it’s like that. I don’t say it’s otherwise. I don’t say it’s not so. And I don’t deny it’s not so.’ "

msgctxt "dn1:2.25.11"
msgid "Idaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā amarāvikkhepikā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ. (2: 14) "
msgstr "This is the second ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely when resorting to evasiveness and equivocation. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.26, pts-vp-pli1.27, sc102
msgctxt "dn1:2.26.1"
msgid "Tatiye ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha amarāvikkhepikā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ? "
msgstr "And what is the third ground on which they rely? "

msgctxt "dn1:2.26.2"
msgid "Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ‘idaṃ kusalan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti, ‘idaṃ akusalan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti. "
msgstr "It’s when some ascetic or brahmin doesn’t truly understand what is skillful and what is unskillful. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.26.3"
msgid "Tassa evaṃ hoti: "
msgstr "They think: "

msgctxt "dn1:2.26.4"
msgid "‘ahaṃ kho “idaṃ kusalan”ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāmi, “idaṃ akusalan”ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāmi. "
msgstr "‘I don’t truly understand what is skillful and what is unskillful. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.26.5"
msgid "Ahañce kho pana “idaṃ kusalan”ti yathābhūtaṃ appajānanto “idaṃ akusalan”ti yathābhūtaṃ appajānanto “idaṃ kusalan”ti vā byākareyyaṃ, “idaṃ akusalan”ti vā byākareyyaṃ; "
msgstr "Suppose I were to declare that something was skillful or unskillful. "

#. VAR: bhindantā → vobhindantā (bj, pts1)
msgctxt "dn1:2.26.6"
msgid "santi hi kho samaṇabrāhmaṇā paṇḍitā nipuṇā kataparappavādā vālavedhirūpā, te bhindantā maññe caranti paññāgatena diṭṭhigatāni, "
msgstr "There are clever ascetics and brahmins who are subtle, accomplished in the doctrines of others, hair-splitters. You’d think they live to demolish convictions with their intellect. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.26.7"
msgid "te maṃ tattha samanuyuñjeyyuṃ samanugāheyyuṃ samanubhāseyyuṃ. "
msgstr "They might pursue, press, and grill me about that. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.26.8"
msgid "Ye maṃ tattha samanuyuñjeyyuṃ samanugāheyyuṃ samanubhāseyyuṃ, tesāhaṃ na sampāyeyyaṃ. "
msgstr "I’d be stumped by such a grilling. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.26.9"
msgid "Yesāhaṃ na sampāyeyyaṃ, so mamassa vighāto. "
msgstr "That would be stressful for me, "

msgctxt "dn1:2.26.10"
msgid "Yo mamassa vighāto, so mamassa antarāyo’ti. "
msgstr "and that stress would be an obstacle.’ "

msgctxt "dn1:2.26.11"
msgid "Iti so anuyogabhayā anuyogaparijegucchā nevidaṃ kusalanti byākaroti, na panidaṃ akusalanti byākaroti, tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭho samāno vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjati amarāvikkhepaṃ: "
msgstr "So from fear and disgust with examination they avoid stating whether something is skillful or unskillful. Whenever they’re asked a question, they resort to evasiveness and equivocation: "

msgctxt "dn1:2.26.12"
msgid "‘evantipi me no; tathātipi me no; aññathātipi me no; notipi me no; no notipi me no’ti. "
msgstr "‘I don’t say it’s like this. I don’t say it’s like that. I don’t say it’s otherwise. I don’t say it’s not so. And I don’t deny it’s not so.’ "

msgctxt "dn1:2.26.13"
msgid "Idaṃ, bhikkhave, tatiyaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā amarāvikkhepikā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ. (3: 15) "
msgstr "This is the third ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely when resorting to evasiveness and equivocation. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.27, sc103
msgctxt "dn1:2.27.1"
msgid "Catutthe ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha amarāvikkhepikā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ? "
msgstr "And what is the fourth ground on which they rely? "

msgctxt "dn1:2.27.2"
msgid "Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā mando hoti momūho. "
msgstr "It’s when some ascetic or brahmin is dull and stupid. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.27.3"
msgid "So mandattā momūhattā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭho samāno vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjati amarāvikkhepaṃ: "
msgstr "Because of that, whenever they’re asked a question, they resort to evasiveness and equivocation: "

msgctxt "dn1:2.27.4"
msgid "‘atthi paro loko’ti iti ce maṃ pucchasi, ‘atthi paro loko’ti iti ce me assa, ‘atthi paro loko’ti iti te naṃ byākareyyaṃ, "
msgstr "‘Suppose you were to ask me whether there is another world. If I believed there was, I would say so. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.27.5"
msgid "‘evantipi me no, tathātipi me no, aññathātipi me no, notipi me no, no notipi me no’ti. "
msgstr "But I don’t say it’s like this. I don’t say it’s like that. I don’t say it’s otherwise. I don’t say it’s not so. And I don’t deny it’s not so. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.27.6"
msgid "‘Natthi paro loko … pe … "
msgstr "Suppose you were to ask me whether there is no other world … "

msgctxt "dn1:2.27.7"
msgid "‘atthi ca natthi ca paro loko … pe … "
msgstr "whether there both is and is not another world … "

msgctxt "dn1:2.27.8"
msgid "‘nevatthi na natthi paro loko … pe … "
msgstr "whether there neither is nor is not another world … "

msgctxt "dn1:2.27.9"
msgid "‘atthi sattā opapātikā … pe … "
msgstr "whether there are beings who are reborn spontaneously … "

msgctxt "dn1:2.27.10"
msgid "‘natthi sattā opapātikā … pe … "
msgstr "whether there are not beings who are reborn spontaneously … "

msgctxt "dn1:2.27.11"
msgid "‘atthi ca natthi ca sattā opapātikā … pe … "
msgstr "whether there both are and are not beings who are reborn spontaneously … "

msgctxt "dn1:2.27.12"
msgid "‘nevatthi na natthi sattā opapātikā … pe … "
msgstr "whether there neither are nor are not beings who are reborn spontaneously … "

msgctxt "dn1:2.27.13"
msgid "‘atthi sukatadukkaṭānaṃ kammānaṃ phalaṃ vipāko … pe … "
msgstr "whether there is fruit and result of good and bad deeds … "

msgctxt "dn1:2.27.14"
msgid "‘natthi sukatadukkaṭānaṃ kammānaṃ phalaṃ vipāko … pe … "
msgstr "whether there is not fruit and result of good and bad deeds … "

msgctxt "dn1:2.27.15"
msgid "‘atthi ca natthi ca sukatadukkaṭānaṃ kammānaṃ phalaṃ vipāko … pe … "
msgstr "whether there both is and is not fruit and result of good and bad deeds … "

msgctxt "dn1:2.27.16"
msgid "‘nevatthi na natthi sukatadukkaṭānaṃ kammānaṃ phalaṃ vipāko … pe … "
msgstr "whether there neither is nor is not fruit and result of good and bad deeds … "

msgctxt "dn1:2.27.17"
msgid "‘hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā … pe … "
msgstr "whether a Realized One exists after death … "

msgctxt "dn1:2.27.18"
msgid "‘na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā … pe … "
msgstr "whether a Realized One doesn’t exist after death … "

#. VAR: hoti ca na ca hoti → hoti ca na hoti ca (bj, pts1, mr)
msgctxt "dn1:2.27.19"
msgid "‘hoti ca na ca hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā … pe … "
msgstr "whether a Realized One both exists and doesn’t exist after death … "

msgctxt "dn1:2.27.20"
msgid "‘neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti iti ce maṃ pucchasi, ‘neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti iti ce me assa, ‘neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti iti te naṃ byākareyyaṃ, "
msgstr "whether a Realized One neither exists nor doesn’t exist after death. If I believed there was, I would say so. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.27.21"
msgid "‘evantipi me no, tathātipi me no, aññathātipi me no, notipi me no, no notipi me no’ti. "
msgstr "But I don’t say it’s like this. I don’t say it’s like that. I don’t say it’s otherwise. I don’t say it’s not so. And I don’t deny it’s not so.’ "

msgctxt "dn1:2.27.22"
msgid "Idaṃ, bhikkhave, catutthaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā amarāvikkhepikā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ. (4: 16) "
msgstr "This is the fourth ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely when resorting to evasiveness and equivocation. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.28, pts-vp-pli1.28, sc104
msgctxt "dn1:2.28.1"
msgid "Imehi kho te, bhikkhave, samaṇabrāhmaṇā amarāvikkhepikā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ catūhi vatthūhi. "
msgstr "These are the four grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins who are equivocators resort to evasiveness and equivocation whenever they’re asked a question. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.28.2"
msgid "Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā amarāvikkhepikā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ, sabbe te imeheva catūhi vatthūhi, etesaṃ vā aññatarena, natthi ito bahiddhā … "
msgstr "Any ascetics and brahmins who resort to equivocation do so on one or other of these four grounds. Outside of this there is none. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.28.3"
msgid "pe … "
msgstr "The Realized One understands this … "

msgctxt "dn1:2.28.4"
msgid "yehi tathāgatassa yathābhuccaṃ vaṇṇaṃ sammā vadamānā vadeyyuṃ. "
msgstr "And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things. "

#. HTML: </p><h4>
msgctxt "dn1:2.28.5"
msgid "3.1.5. Adhiccasamuppannavāda "
msgstr "3.1.5. Doctrines of Origination by Chance "

#. HTML: </h4><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.30, sc105
msgctxt "dn1:2.30.1"
msgid "Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā adhiccasamuppannikā adhiccasamuppannaṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti dvīhi vatthūhi. "
msgstr "There are some ascetics and brahmins who theorize about chance. They assert that the self and the cosmos arose by chance on two grounds. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.30.2"
msgid "Te ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha adhiccasamuppannikā adhiccasamuppannaṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti dvīhi vatthūhi? "
msgstr "And what are the two grounds on which they rely? "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.31, pts-vp-pli1.29, sc106
msgctxt "dn1:2.31.1"
msgid "Santi, bhikkhave, asaññasattā nāma devā. "
msgstr "There are gods named ‘non-percipient beings’. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.31.2"
msgid "Saññuppādā ca pana te devā tamhā kāyā cavanti. "
msgstr "When perception arises they pass away from that host of gods. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.31.3"
msgid "Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, bhikkhave, vijjati, yaṃ aññataro satto tamhā kāyā cavitvā itthattaṃ āgacchati. "
msgstr "It’s possible that one of those beings passes away from that host and is reborn in this state of existence. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.31.4"
msgid "Itthattaṃ āgato samāno agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati. "
msgstr "Having done so, they go forth from the lay life to homelessness. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.31.5"
msgid "Agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito samāno ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte saññuppādaṃ anussarati, tato paraṃ nānussarati. "
msgstr "By dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus, they experience an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they recollect the arising of perception, but no further. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.31.6"
msgid "So evamāha: "
msgstr "They say: "

msgctxt "dn1:2.31.7"
msgid "‘adhiccasamuppanno attā ca loko ca. "
msgstr "‘The self and the cosmos arose by chance. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.31.8"
msgid "Taṃ kissa hetu? "
msgstr "Why is that? "

msgctxt "dn1:2.31.9"
msgid "Ahañhi pubbe nāhosiṃ, somhi etarahi ahutvā santatāya pariṇato’ti. "
msgstr "Because formerly I didn’t exist. Now, having not been, I’ve sprung into existence.’ "

msgctxt "dn1:2.31.10"
msgid "Idaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā adhiccasamuppannikā adhiccasamuppannaṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti. (1: 17) "
msgstr "This is the first ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the self and the cosmos arose by chance. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.32, sc107
msgctxt "dn1:2.32.1"
msgid "Dutiye ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha adhiccasamuppannikā adhiccasamuppannaṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti? "
msgstr "And what is the second ground on which they rely? "

msgctxt "dn1:2.32.2"
msgid "Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā takkī hoti vīmaṃsī. "
msgstr "It’s when some ascetic or brahmin relies on logic and inquiry. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.32.3"
msgid "So takkapariyāhataṃ vīmaṃsānucaritaṃ sayampaṭibhānaṃ evamāha: "
msgstr "They speak of what they have worked out by logic, following a line of inquiry, expressing their own perspective: "

msgctxt "dn1:2.32.4"
msgid "‘adhiccasamuppanno attā ca loko cā’ti. "
msgstr "‘The self and the cosmos arose by chance.’ "

msgctxt "dn1:2.32.5"
msgid "Idaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā adhiccasamuppannikā adhiccasamuppannaṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti. (2: 18) "
msgstr "This is the second ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the self and the cosmos arose by chance. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.33, sc108
msgctxt "dn1:2.33.1"
msgid "Imehi kho te, bhikkhave, samaṇabrāhmaṇā adhiccasamuppannikā adhiccasamuppannaṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti dvīhi vatthūhi. "
msgstr "These are the two grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins who theorize about chance assert that the self and the cosmos arose by chance. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.33.2"
msgid "Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā adhiccasamuppannikā adhiccasamuppannaṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti, sabbe te imeheva dvīhi vatthūhi, etesaṃ vā aññatarena, natthi ito bahiddhā … "
msgstr "Any ascetics and brahmins who theorize about chance do so on one or other of these two grounds. Outside of this there is none. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.33.3"
msgid "pe … "
msgstr "The Realized One understands this … "

msgctxt "dn1:2.33.4"
msgid "yehi tathāgatassa yathābhuccaṃ vaṇṇaṃ sammā vadamānā vadeyyuṃ. "
msgstr "And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.35, sc109
msgctxt "dn1:2.35.1"
msgid "Imehi kho te, bhikkhave, samaṇabrāhmaṇā pubbantakappikā pubbantānudiṭṭhino pubbantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti aṭṭhārasahi vatthūhi. "
msgstr "These are the eighteen grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins who theorize about the past assert various hypotheses concerning the past. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.35.2"
msgid "Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā pubbantakappikā pubbantānudiṭṭhino pubbantamārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti, sabbe te imeheva aṭṭhārasahi vatthūhi, etesaṃ vā aññatarena, natthi ito bahiddhā. "
msgstr "Any ascetics and brahmins who theorize about the past do so on one or other of these eighteen grounds. Outside of this there is none. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.36, sc110
msgctxt "dn1:2.36.1"
msgid "Tayidaṃ, bhikkhave, tathāgato pajānāti: "
msgstr "The Realized One understands this: "

msgctxt "dn1:2.36.2"
msgid "‘ime diṭṭhiṭṭhānā evaṅgahitā evaṃparāmaṭṭhā evaṅgatikā bhavanti evaṃabhisamparāyā’ti. "
msgstr "‘If you hold on to and attach to these grounds for views it leads to such and such a destiny in the next life.’ "

msgctxt "dn1:2.36.3"
msgid "Tañca tathāgato pajānāti, tato ca uttaritaraṃ pajānāti, tañca pajānanaṃ na parāmasati, aparāmasato cassa paccattaññeva nibbuti viditā. "
msgstr "He understands this, and what goes beyond this. Yet since he does not misapprehend that understanding, he has realized extinguishment within himself. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.36.4"
msgid "Vedanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ viditvā anupādāvimutto, bhikkhave, tathāgato. "
msgstr "Having truly understood the origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape from feelings, the Realized One is freed through not grasping. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-vp-pli1.30, sc111
msgctxt "dn1:2.36.5"
msgid "Ime kho te, bhikkhave, dhammā gambhīrā duddasā duranubodhā santā paṇītā atakkāvacarā nipuṇā paṇḍitavedanīyā, ye tathāgato sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti, yehi tathāgatassa yathābhuccaṃ vaṇṇaṃ sammā vadamānā vadeyyuṃ. "
msgstr "These are the principles—deep, hard to see, hard to understand, peaceful, sublime, beyond the scope of reason, subtle, comprehensible to the astute—which the Realized One makes known after realizing them with his own insight. And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things. "

#. HTML: </p><p class="endsection">
msgctxt "dn1:2.36.6"
msgid "Dutiyabhāṇavāro. "
msgstr " "

#. HTML: </p><h3>
msgctxt "dn1:2.36.7"
msgid "3.2. Aparantakappika "
msgstr "3.2. Theories About the Future "

#. HTML: </h3><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.37, sc112
msgctxt "dn1:2.37.1"
msgid "Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā aparantakappikā aparantānudiṭṭhino, aparantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti catucattārīsāya vatthūhi. "
msgstr "There are some ascetics and brahmins who theorize about the future, and assert various hypotheses concerning the future on forty-four grounds. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.37.2"
msgid "Te ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha aparantakappikā aparantānudiṭṭhino aparantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti catucattārīsāya vatthūhi? "
msgstr "And what are the forty-four grounds on which they rely? "

#. HTML: </p><h4>
msgctxt "dn1:2.37.3"
msgid "3.2.1. Saññīvāda "
msgstr "3.2.1. Percipient Life After Death "

#. HTML: </h4><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.38, pts-vp-pli1.31, sc113
msgctxt "dn1:2.38.1"
msgid "Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā uddhamāghātanikā saññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti soḷasahi vatthūhi. "
msgstr "There are some ascetics and brahmins who say there is life after death, and assert that the self lives on after death in a percipient form on sixteen grounds. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.38.2"
msgid "Te ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha uddhamāghātanikā saññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti soḷasahi vatthūhi? "
msgstr "And what are the sixteen grounds on which they rely? "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc114
msgctxt "dn1:2.38.3"
msgid "‘Rūpī attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā saññī’ti naṃ paññapenti. (1: 19) "
msgstr "They assert: ‘The self is sound and percipient after death, and it is physical … "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc115
msgctxt "dn1:2.38.4"
msgid "‘Arūpī attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā saññī’ti naṃ paññapenti. (2: 20) "
msgstr "non-physical … "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc116
msgctxt "dn1:2.38.5"
msgid "‘Rūpī ca arūpī ca attā hoti … pe …. (3: 21) "
msgstr "both physical and non-physical … "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc117
msgctxt "dn1:2.38.6"
msgid "‘Nevarūpī nārūpī attā hoti …. (4: 22) "
msgstr "neither physical nor non-physical … "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc118
msgctxt "dn1:2.38.7"
msgid "‘Antavā attā hoti …. (5: 23) "
msgstr "finite … "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc119
msgctxt "dn1:2.38.8"
msgid "‘Anantavā attā hoti …. (6: 24) "
msgstr "infinite … "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc120
msgctxt "dn1:2.38.9"
msgid "‘Antavā ca anantavā ca attā hoti …. (7: 25) "
msgstr "both finite and infinite … "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc121
msgctxt "dn1:2.38.10"
msgid "‘Nevantavā nānantavā attā hoti …. (8: 26) "
msgstr "neither finite nor infinite … "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc122
msgctxt "dn1:2.38.11"
msgid "‘Ekattasaññī attā hoti …. (9: 27) "
msgstr "of unified perception … "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc123
msgctxt "dn1:2.38.12"
msgid "‘Nānattasaññī attā hoti …. (10: 28) "
msgstr "of diverse perception … "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc124
msgctxt "dn1:2.38.13"
msgid "‘Parittasaññī attā hoti …. (11: 29) "
msgstr "of limited perception … "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc125
msgctxt "dn1:2.38.14"
msgid "‘Appamāṇasaññī attā hoti …. (12: 30) "
msgstr "of limitless perception … "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc126
msgctxt "dn1:2.38.15"
msgid "‘Ekantasukhī attā hoti …. (13: 31) "
msgstr "experiences nothing but happiness … "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc127
msgctxt "dn1:2.38.16"
msgid "‘Ekantadukkhī attā hoti …. (14: 32) "
msgstr "experiences nothing but suffering … "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc128
msgctxt "dn1:2.38.17"
msgid "‘Sukhadukkhī attā hoti …. (15: 33) "
msgstr "experiences both happiness and suffering … "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc129
msgctxt "dn1:2.38.18"
msgid "‘Adukkhamasukhī attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā saññī’ti naṃ paññapenti. (16: 34) "
msgstr "experiences neither happiness nor suffering.’ "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs2.39, pts-vp-pli1.32, sc130
msgctxt "dn1:2.39.1"
msgid "Imehi kho te, bhikkhave, samaṇabrāhmaṇā uddhamāghātanikā saññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti soḷasahi vatthūhi. "
msgstr "These are the sixteen grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins assert that the self lives on after death in a percipient form. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.39.2"
msgid "Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā uddhamāghātanikā saññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti, sabbe te imeheva soḷasahi vatthūhi, etesaṃ vā aññatarena, natthi ito bahiddhā … "
msgstr "Any ascetics and brahmins who assert that the self lives on after death in a percipient form do so on one or other of these sixteen grounds. Outside of this there is none. "

msgctxt "dn1:2.39.3"
msgid "pe … "
msgstr "The Realized One understands this … "

msgctxt "dn1:2.39.4"
msgid "yehi tathāgatassa yathābhuccaṃ vaṇṇaṃ sammā vadamānā vadeyyuṃ. "
msgstr "And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things. "

#. HTML: </p><h4>
msgctxt "dn1:2.39.5"
msgid "3.2.2. Asaññīvāda "
msgstr "3.2.2. Non-Percipient Life After Death "

#. HTML: </h4><p>
#. REF: pts-cs3.1, sc131
msgctxt "dn1:3.1.1"
msgid "Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā uddhamāghātanikā asaññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ asaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti aṭṭhahi vatthūhi. "
msgstr "There are some ascetics and brahmins who say there is life after death, and assert that the self lives on after death in a non-percipient form on eight grounds. "

msgctxt "dn1:3.1.2"
msgid "Te ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha uddhamāghātanikā asaññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ asaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti aṭṭhahi vatthūhi? "
msgstr "And what are the eight grounds on which they rely? "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs3.2, sc132
msgctxt "dn1:3.2.1"
msgid "‘Rūpī attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā asaññī’ti naṃ paññapenti. (1: 35) "
msgstr "They assert: ‘The self is sound and non-percipient after death, and it is physical … "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc133
msgctxt "dn1:3.2.2"
msgid "‘Arūpī attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā asaññī’ti naṃ paññapenti. (2: 36) "
msgstr "non-physical … "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc134
msgctxt "dn1:3.2.3"
msgid "‘Rūpī ca arūpī ca attā hoti … pe …. (3: 37) "
msgstr "both physical and non-physical … "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc135
msgctxt "dn1:3.2.4"
msgid "‘Nevarūpī nārūpī attā hoti …. (4: 38) "
msgstr "neither physical nor non-physical … "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc136
msgctxt "dn1:3.2.5"
msgid "‘Antavā attā hoti …. (5: 39) "
msgstr "finite … "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc137
msgctxt "dn1:3.2.6"
msgid "‘Anantavā attā hoti …. (6: 40) "
msgstr "infinite … "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc138
msgctxt "dn1:3.2.7"
msgid "‘Antavā ca anantavā ca attā hoti …. (7: 41) "
msgstr "both finite and infinite … "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc139
msgctxt "dn1:3.2.8"
msgid "‘Nevantavā nānantavā attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā asaññī’ti naṃ paññapenti. (8: 42) "
msgstr "neither finite nor infinite.’ "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs3.3, pts-vp-pli1.33, sc140
msgctxt "dn1:3.3.1"
msgid "Imehi kho te, bhikkhave, samaṇabrāhmaṇā uddhamāghātanikā asaññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ asaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti aṭṭhahi vatthūhi. "
msgstr "These are the eight grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins assert that the self lives on after death in a non-percipient form. "

msgctxt "dn1:3.3.2"
msgid "Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā uddhamāghātanikā asaññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ asaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti, sabbe te imeheva aṭṭhahi vatthūhi, etesaṃ vā aññatarena, natthi ito bahiddhā … "
msgstr "Any ascetics and brahmins who assert that the self lives on after death in a non-percipient form do so on one or other of these eight grounds. Outside of this there is none. "

msgctxt "dn1:3.3.3"
msgid "pe … "
msgstr "The Realized One understands this … "

msgctxt "dn1:3.3.4"
msgid "yehi tathāgatassa yathābhuccaṃ vaṇṇaṃ sammā vadamānā vadeyyuṃ. "
msgstr "And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things. "

#. HTML: </p><h4>
msgctxt "dn1:3.3.5"
msgid "3.2.3. Nevasaññīnāsaññīvāda "
msgstr "3.2.3. Neither Percipient Nor Non-Percipient Life After Death "

#. HTML: </h4><p>
#. REF: pts-cs3.5, sc141
msgctxt "dn1:3.5.1"
msgid "Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā uddhamāghātanikā nevasaññīnāsaññīvādā, uddhamāghātanaṃ nevasaññīnāsaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti aṭṭhahi vatthūhi. "
msgstr "There are some ascetics and brahmins who say there is life after death, and assert that the self lives on after death in a neither percipient nor non-percipient form on eight grounds. "

msgctxt "dn1:3.5.2"
msgid "Te ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha uddhamāghātanikā nevasaññīnāsaññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ nevasaññīnāsaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti aṭṭhahi vatthūhi? "
msgstr "And what are the eight grounds on which they rely? "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-cs3.6, sc142
msgctxt "dn1:3.6.1"
msgid "‘Rūpī attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā nevasaññīnāsaññī’ti naṃ paññapenti. (1: 43) "
msgstr "They assert: ‘The self is sound and neither percipient nor non-percipient after death, and it is physical … "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc143
msgctxt "dn1:3.6.2"
